tip.text:
P. Franco is a bit of an institution on the low intervention wine scene - almost single handedly making 'natural' the coolest wine for Londoners to drink. By day it's a mighty friendly shop stocking unpretentious liquids - of varying price range. (France and Italy dominate the wine offerings but you can still expect a hefty selection of bottles here, from the USA to Australia.)

By night (four a week) it becomes one of the most intimate eating experiences about. Where guest chefs work their magic over two induction hobs and serve up all sorts of goodies to a large communal table. Though cooking styles change depending on who's in the kitchen, you can always expect high calibre grub from these guys - paired with intriguing natural wine selects. Our fave bit? The way beginners and wine geeks are welcomed with equally smiley faces.

Kitchen times:
Thurs: 6-9
Fri-Sat: 6-10
Sun: 2-9

Rawduck lays on some quality all-day dining with fresh seasonal produce at the centre of their breakfast, lunch and dinner menus. We've been known to head there for breakfasts of home-made granolas, oats, and egg dishes with middle eastern bread; comforting pasta lunches and more luxurious dinners.

The drinks are just as exciting here with a rotating list of natural and biodynamic wines and house kombuchas, drinking vinegars and kefirs. Blimey that's a lot of fermenting. Over the summer grab an outdoor bench to nibble your raspberry upside down cake with Iranian pistachios and orange blossom yoghurt. Happy days.

Tucked away behind Hackney’s Wilton Way, Wolfie’s is a teeny tiny, dog-friendly bar - there’s space for about 15 so we reckon it’s got to be E8’s smallest drinking hole. Luckily there's plenty of pavement overspill space in the summertime.

It's the perfect spot to enjoy a glass of biodynamic orange wine and a selection of charcuteries, but the cocktail list is banging too; we rate the White Wolfgroni, made with suze, gin and white vermouth. A masterclass in flattering lighting and artfully distressed decor, Wolfie’s is only open Thursday to Sunday evenings. Hot tip: pop down on Sundays for some candle-lit live music and good vibes.

There's a few things we've come to expect from the P. Franco team: friendly staff, high-brow cooking and an eye-opening selection of natural wine (some delicious, some strange but all dutifully explained to novices). So when we heard they were opening a restaurant in London Fields, we knew it would be a corker. As its name suggests Bright is well lit, airy, filled with plants, graphic posters and low-key furniture. A pretty chill backdrop for some sumptuous food.

We were won over by the simple flavours of al dente asparagus steamed in all sorts of fresh herbs and drizzled with lemon verbena oil; and some more surprising concoctions like a cold almond soup topped with crab meat and olive oil; or the soft, crispy pleasures of a Japanese katsu sando sandwich in white bread. Unlike a lot of the small plate restos of East London, portions don't leave you feeling hard done by (you won't find yourself dividing out the last broad bean or trying to share a prime number of tortellini). In fact our plate of pasta with sausage meat ragu was just the right size, thanks.

As both a wine bar and deli Furanxo has all the hook ups for some seriously choice eats. We watched them slice Iberico bellota ham before our very eyes and had to hold back the temptation to go all caveman. Thankfully, it's easy to find 1001 distractions, from the staffs' words of wine wisdom to the curious cans of seafood and preserves. Canned octopus, anyone?

Furanxo's airy space transitions seamlessly from daytime bodega to bar, packed most nights with a buzzy mix of languages and personalities. Carefully selected wines by the glass go hand in hand with their cheese and charcuterie boards - which can also be packed up in quaint parcels ready for a picnic or a caj get together.

Roll call for all wine bar junkies 'cause this is a place for you. Sporting a charming little walled garden in the back, helpful staff, tasting evenings, cheese boards and quite the selection of cured meats (wild boar for you, sir?) Newcomer Wines is a bit of a showstopper.

How does it stand out from all the other wine bars in Dalston? With 250 wines mostly from Austria and a few neighbouring European countries too. Yep, you've got your work cut out for you: every wine has a delicious tale to tell, and if you have the time then they have the stories.

Look out for events and pop ups here too!

From the team that brought you Sager and Wilde Wine Bar comes this restaurant. A low key Californian-inspired spot hidden under a railway arch next to Bethnal Green station. These guys have some great lunch choices and their evening set menu is full of tasty bites.

As if all that isn't enough they've just opened an Old Fashioned bar on the mezzanine. Their classic cocktails had us from the off but now they've gone and done us proud with an olive oil Old Fashioned, a burnt maple Old Fashioned and a tonka bean and rooibos Old Fashioned. Perfect to cut through the delightfully greasy anchovy and lardo on toast.

If you’re in Stoke Newington looking for a spot with a little romance, Rubedo is your man: a dimly lit, understated natural wine bar serving up delightful plates of Italian food. The place exudes Continental charm with a scattering of wooden tables under big windows looking out at Church Street and a short blackboard menu.

Stop by for some gnocco fritto (puffy, flaky deep-fried bread) draped in prosciutto and wash it down with a perfectly matched raw prosecco. Or a plate of slow braised pork cheek with a sharp radicchio and blood orange salad with a glass of something red and velvety. Everything on the menu here is as considered as the wine list and you can't really go too far wrong - just don’t be shy to ask for pairing recommendations.

This taproom and deli offers 20 different natural and craft wines all available to be bought by the bag (or other reusable container of your choice). Their whole environmentally friendly angle means wine costs a little less (happy days) and stays fresher for longer in their eco bags.

You can also sit in, have a guzzle of the good stuff, and nibble on prime deli selects. Dalston might not be crying out for another wine bar, but that's what it's got.

When you think of wineries and the wine making process you probably don't imagine it all going down in Bethnal Green. Well the chaps at Renegade get their grapes from small growers in Europe and the UK then process, age, bottle, cork, label, and wax their bottles in their lovely railway arch spot near the station. Oh and all those grapes are squashed between their sexy toes.

They have one white (Sauv Blanc baby) and a red wine made with Bacchus grapes. It is part fermented with skins on, part fermented in oak barrels and a stainless steel tank. Whaaaa? Give it a sniff and you might just catch some elderflower and green apple scents. Taste it and you might just get hints of citrus fruit. Or you might just sip it and think "Yeah that's good stuff". Who are we to say? On Fridays and Saturdays you can sit inside or outside, sip on their vino and even bring your dog along. If you do, it's highly likely Renegade will propel your furry friend into Insta fame.

This cocktail bar has nabbed all the best bits of French culture to make something pretty darn sophistiqué. The decor and vibe is classy as hell: not a gimmick in sight, and plenty of grown up flavours with spirits like Calvados and Armagnac featuring heavily. Even the 'fun' choices are très chic: the piña colada with coconut sorbet and Moët & Chandon was a perfect dessert alternative. There's many a champagne cocktail (once you pop a bottle of Moët you as well pour it in everything right?) though we fell hard for the 'First Things First'. Whisky based with dry vermouth and a touch of fruitiness, we want them to bottle it so we can drink it forever more.

There's also a fine nibble to be had with charcuterie boards and some pongy French cheese platters (pongy in the best possible way). What with the friendly service, it's all pretty smart-casual-smart and we quite like it.

We may not be the savviest wine connoisseurs but there's no way we'd let that stand in the way of the beauty that is Sager + Wilde. This fine wine bar nestled on Hackney Road just ooooozes cool. Whichever vino it is you fancy - full-bodied, crisp and dry, fruity, a dash of sparkle - they'll take the time get to know your flavour.

Perfect to impress on date nights, mate nights, solo tipple nights... we ain't judging. Make sure to grab a small plate or cheese board for starters. Later when the wine's flowing freely, hit up the grilled cheese.

Visiting Brawn is like visiting an old friend - tucked away off Columbia Road, it’s warm, inviting, and you can just slot into their simple dining room like you would a familiar couch, before getting the kind of comfortable that you usually reserve for less public settings. Blame it on their bang-up selection of vino - made up mostly of natural wines from small growers, it's the kind of wine list that would make your snobbiest sommelier friend weak in the knees.

And the food is just as likely to induce some friendly feelings - seasonal, uncomplicated dishes made with vibrant British ingredients that swell with flavour. The menu is often comically terse, but trust us, these guys can take humble dishes and make them magic.

With dual citizenship from Italy and France, this wine shop-cum-bar-cum-restaurant is dripping with European charm: exposed brick walls lined with fantastic wines; an ever changing menu of locally sourced seasonal small plates; and more rustic cosiness than you could shake a molten candle stick in an empty bottle of red at. We had Philippe tending to our needs, and his in depth knowledge about the wine, along with his ability to articulate himself in a language we could understand (wait, what’s a tannin again?) was the perfect level of informative.

The food, however, needed no introduction. Chef Sophie (previously of The River Café) cooked us up a storm; from the first bite of her homemade bresaola with lemon and parmesan to the last of her polenta cake with Kentish rhubarb and crème fraîche, she had us hooked with simple and subtle flavours. The highlight for us, though, has to be the burrata with roast English asparagus and leaves from the Lea Valley - it was an absolute delight. Located on the rough and ready stretch of Roman Road just below Vicky Park, this feels like a diamond in the rough, ripe for date night or some solo indulgence.

Food is served from 6pm.

Wine, cheese and charcuterie - three staples of any balanced diet. Yield N16 is all about biodynamic wine, so it's the perfect place to learn a little something. The grape juice is accompanied by British cheese boards and indulgent charcuterie boards (all served with chutney, crackers and really really local honey).

It's the kinda neighbourhood hang out to take your most philosophical mates to and delve deep into the world's problems over wine and cured meats. A big selection of cured meats: chilli and oregano salami, saucisson with black peppercorns, fennel & garlic salami, bresaola, coppa, lomo and pepperoni sausage. Phew that's a whole hunk 'a meat.

It's not unusual to meet a Tuscan who looks down on food and wine from the rest of Italy. Now we think this is a tad silly, but to be fair to 'em they do come from a pretty bountiful land. If you're lucky enough to pay it a visit you'll likely tour the rolling hills covered in vines - the land of Chianti Classico. Brothers Marco and Lacopo Rossi thought they'd bring a little taste of the area to us uneducated lot, concentrating their efforts on natural and craft wine.

The food is hella traditional too, with the likes of polenta with wild boar or 'ribollita', a hearty peasant soup made with cannellini beans, bread and vegetables. Sounds a bit meh but it's a Tuscan classic - thick, comforting and surprisingly yummy. The mains are good but if you can't hang about get them to help you pick a cured meat and organic wine combo, then sit back and enjoy. Perfect to duck away from the madness of Brick Lane.

Tapas-style small plates might be the new norm but it wasn't always that way, honestly. Tapas Brindisa's Borough Market outpost was one of the first and they do what they do pretty well. The food is good quality and reflects everything you know and like about Spanish cuisine, with freshly prepared dishes featuring that gambas al ajillo, pulpo a la gallega, arroz negro and, for you comfort seekers, patatas bravas. Add G&Ts and a strong list of wines, sherry and liqueurs and you've got yourself the makings of a good evening.

The only drawback is bang for your buck - it's a little steep for not huge portions. It can still get pretty busy though - or buzzy if you prefer - and on sunnier days the terrace out back provides the perfect backdrop for pretending you're really on holiday in Spain.

When, like Jana and Ali, you're married and have a wine shop that specialises in organic vino, local craft beer and selected spirits, then the obvious next step is a wine bar AND restaurant. Isn't it? Enter Forest Bar + Kitchen, delighting the tongues of Walthamstow with fine wine and modern European small plates. Food is seasonal (obvs), punchy, and served around a large communal table. And the wine? Well it's a mixture of organic, biodynamic and natural of course.

If the promise of mussels, nduja and fried bread or a plate of pickled egg, pea shoots and girolles won't get you up to Walthy we don't know what will.

Just around the corner from Canonbury Station, you'll find Vins patiently lying in wait with a stellar wine list and some accompanying tasty treats to draw you in. Wine bars can be an intimidating affair, but Vins go out of their way to eschew the snobbier side of things. For instance, instead of notifying you of a wine's ‘leathery mid-palette and tannic finish’, the menu focuses on short but sweet synopses of each bottle. Statements like ‘oozing minerality and freshness’ or ‘a pale, hazy, lip-smacker’ smoothly lulled us towards our chosen glasses. A nice touch for us Yellow Tail/Barefoot aficionados.

The menu changes regularly so there’s no point recommending the fried taleggio sandwich, the hake with potted shrimps or the blueberry bakewell tart. Instead we will just say the food is gawjus. We really liked it. You should go.

If you consider yourself an aficionado of fine wine (or you just really dig that tasty grape juice), then Bottles is the spot for you. With over 180 labels of wine to choose from, whether it be old or new world whites and reds, roses, or big ol' magnums for the big shots - there's something for every palette and wallet size.

We went for a tidy glass of Italian chardonnay and paired it with a creamy blob of burrata that came majestically sat in a tangy tomato elixir. We also tucked into a yummy plate of puttanesca, complete with home-made pasta and delicate peppery undertones. All-in-all, a sophisticated spot with refined offerings - check it out if you ever find yourselves thirsty in Spitalfields.
